<PubmedArticleSet>
<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41672057</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1555-0273</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>21</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sports physiology and performance</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Exploratory Comparison of Cardiac Left and Right Ventricle and Skeletal Muscle Glucose Uptake After Exercise.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>492</StartPage><EndPage>496</EndPage><MedlinePgn>492-496</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijspp.2025-0179</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study aimed to measure and compare postexercise glucose uptake (GU) in the left and right ventricular myocardium (LV and RV, respectively) and quadriceps femoris (QF) muscle.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Six recreationally active males (22 [2] y; VO2peak 54 [6]&#xa0;mL/kg/min; maximal power 350 [22]&#xa0;W) completed a 30-minute cycling bout. The protocol comprised 10&#xa0;minutes at 100&#xa0;W, a ramp to exhaustion (+25&#xa0;W/min), 1&#xa0;min passive recovery, then cycling at 75% VO2peak to 30&#xa0;minute GU was quantified with 2-[18F]FDG PET.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Postexercise GU in the LV myocardium (14.1 [5.1] &#x3bc;mol/100&#xa0;g/min) was significantly higher (P &lt; .01) than that in the RV (7.2 [3.2] &#x3bc;mol/100&#xa0;g/min) or QF muscle (6.4 [1.9] &#x3bc;mol/100&#xa0;g/min). GU in the LV and RV correlated strongly (r = .84, P = .039), whereas GU in these ventricles did not correlate with QF GU (P &gt; .27). Circulating venous blood lactate concentration was 1.1 (0.5)&#xa0;mmol/L at rest and peaked at 10.4 (2.6)&#xa0;mmol/L postexercise. Peak lactate tended to correlate positively with GU, particularly in the RV (r = .93, P = .02) and LV (r = .87, P = .055) myocardium, and to a lesser extent in the QF muscle (r = .78, P = .12).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">These findings indicate that the LV myocardium consumes more glucose per unit mass than skeletal muscle after vigorous exercise, whereas the RV shows no such difference.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Heinonen</LastName><ForeName>Ilkka</ForeName><Initials>I</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-8608-4839</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Turku PET Centre, University of Turku and Turku University Hospital, Turku, Finland.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The UKK Institute for Health Promotion Research, Tampere, Finland.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kalliokoski</LastName><ForeName>Kari K</ForeName><Initials>KK</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-8893-7126</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Turku PET Centre, University of Turku and Turku University Hospital, Turku, Finland.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biomedical Engineering, Huazhong University of Science and Technology, Wuhan, HUB, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Born</LastName><ForeName>Dennis-Peter</ForeName><Initials>DP</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1058-4367</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Section for High-Performance Sports, Swiss Swimming Federation, Worblaufen, Switzerland.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department for Elite Sport, Swiss Federal Institute of